metatags.og:description:
1,650 likes, 10 comments - majordomohakanoztunali on June 10, 2025: "INTRODUCING @nyachu_u ● Interview published.

(link in bio)

Introduction

○Jirai Kei fashion emphasizes mass-produced cuteness mixed with subtle rebellion. Do you see your characters as extensions of this rebellion? What emotions or narratives are you encoding into their outfits and accessories?

Nyachu: Yes, ofc!! Although jts not completely jirai kei style, i used similar elemets such as cuts, bandages and scars which are stereotypes of the jirai kei style. Jirai Kei plays with the tension between cuteness and mental health, and I try to reflect that in my characters. Their outfits often mix ribbons or lace with something slightly more 'mentally ill-ish', like bandages, cuts, scars and and a muted color palette. in a way showing the vulnerability and the hidden pain they suffer under the cuteness.

#interview #artdaily #jirai #kei #artistsupport #illustration #animeaesthetic".

metatags.citation_author_institution: School of Professional Communication, Ryerson University, Canada
metatags.title: Frontiers | Mentally Ill and Cute as Hell: Menhera Girls and Portrayals of Self-Injury in Japanese Popular Culture
metatags.citation_abstract: Over the last few decades, self-injury has gained wide visibility in Japanese popular culture from manga (graphic novel), anime (animation), to digital games and fashion. Among the most conspicuous is the emergence of menhera (a portmanteau of “mental health-er”) girls, female characters who exhibit unstable emotionality, obsessive love, and stereotypical self-injurious behaviours such as wrist cutting. Tracing the expansion of this popular cultural slang since 2000, this conceptual paper explores three narrative tropes of menhera – the sad girl, the mad woman, and the cutie. Within these menhera narratives, self-injury functions as a self-sufficient signifier of female vulnerability, monstrosity, and desire for agency. These menhera tropes, each with their unique interpretation of self-injury, have evolved symbiotically with traditional gender norms in Japan, while destabilizing long-standing undesirability of sick/detracted female bodies. Whether someone has encountered this style through social media or anime culture, they're typically looking for guidance on how to create their jirai kei look without appropriating its deeper cultural meanings.
This style represents more than clothing choices—it's a form of emotional expression that resonates with those who find beauty in vulnerability and strength in embracing their complex feelings.
